WEBVTT

00:01.168 --> 00:03.576
He was shackled,
nailed into a packing crate,

00:03.600 --> 00:04.877
the crate is wrapped in chains,

00:04.901 --> 00:05.912
and then the crate is dropped

00:05.936 --> 00:07.413
into the bottom of the East River,

00:07.437 --> 00:08.981
and still he manages to escape.

00:09.005 --> 00:11.217
This is a day in the life of
a federal public defender.

00:11.241 --> 00:12.885
Okay, have you ever made
an elephant disappear?

00:12.909 --> 00:14.220
I got you to dismiss the case against

00:14.244 --> 00:16.322
Victor "The Walrus" Torrazzo last year.

00:16.346 --> 00:18.357
"Houdini's Escapes."
Where did you get this?

00:18.381 --> 00:19.792
The Strand.

00:19.816 --> 00:21.093
Is there anything you don't read?

00:21.117 --> 00:23.963
I generally avoid fantasy,
books about beads,

00:23.987 --> 00:26.098
and used automobile manuals.

00:26.122 --> 00:27.967
Other than that, I'll probably read it.

00:27.991 --> 00:30.203
And when Houdini performed
the underwater box trick

00:30.227 --> 00:32.371
off of Battery Park in 1914,

00:32.395 --> 00:35.208
15,000 people showed up.

00:35.232 --> 00:36.609
Should we go take a look?

00:36.633 --> 00:37.910
Are they all still there?

00:37.934 --> 00:39.045
We can pretend,

00:39.069 --> 00:40.279
and we don't have to go into the office.

00:41.538 --> 00:42.982
Ohh, I have to go into the office.

00:43.006 --> 00:44.850
- No. Really?
- It's your fault.

00:44.874 --> 00:46.652
That's not a nice thing to say.

00:46.676 --> 00:48.354
Drop the charges
and I can hang out all day.

00:48.378 --> 00:50.109
Otherwise, I got to go figure
out how to escape from this.

00:50.134 --> 00:51.157
I can't do that.

00:51.181 --> 00:52.858
I don't even know what that is,
and I know I can't do that.

00:52.882 --> 00:54.393
You know exactly what it is.

00:54.417 --> 00:55.795
Murder?

00:55.819 --> 00:56.963
Don't be afraid of murder.

00:56.987 --> 00:58.431
I am afraid of murder.

00:58.455 --> 00:59.498
D-Did someone say murder?

00:59.522 --> 01:01.534
I think you heard "duty."

01:01.558 --> 01:03.636
It's a joke because murder doesn't
sound anything like duty.

01:03.660 --> 01:05.238
Steve Caldwell, 22,

01:05.262 --> 01:07.673
arrested for strangling
Ellie Mason to death

01:07.697 --> 01:09.542
near a music festival
on Governor's Island.

01:09.566 --> 01:11.110
I heard someone talking
about this on the train.

01:11.134 --> 01:12.812
I heard everybody talking
about this on the train.

01:12.836 --> 01:13.879
I was on my bike,

01:13.903 --> 01:16.215
and it's hard to hear
because of the wind.

01:16.239 --> 01:17.283
Go ahead.

01:17.307 --> 01:18.651
Why do we have this?

01:18.675 --> 01:20.319
The body was found on federal property

01:20.343 --> 01:21.454
near Castle Williams.

01:21.478 --> 01:23.256
NYPD turned it over to the feds.

01:23.280 --> 01:24.690
There are two eyewitnesses

01:24.714 --> 01:27.260
who saw them leave
the music festival together,

01:27.284 --> 01:28.894
his keycard was used

01:28.918 --> 01:30.663
to open a nearby miniature golf course...

01:30.687 --> 01:31.964
where they apparently fooled around

01:31.988 --> 01:33.699
before walking to Castle Williams...

01:33.723 --> 01:35.501
and a medical examiner's report

01:35.525 --> 01:37.336
indicating that she was strangled.

01:37.360 --> 01:39.238
- That's it?
- No.

01:39.262 --> 01:40.439
He also made a statement.

01:40.463 --> 01:42.275
- He confessed?
- According to the complaint.

01:42.299 --> 01:43.309
We need the statement

01:43.333 --> 01:44.844
and any recordings they might have made.

01:44.868 --> 01:46.746
We also need Steve's criminal history

01:46.770 --> 01:47.947
and anything you can find

01:47.971 --> 01:50.182
about the relationship
between Ellie and Steve.

01:50.206 --> 01:52.385
And we need to dig into Ellie. And folks?

01:52.409 --> 01:53.619
Stay sharp because people

01:53.643 --> 01:56.022
aren't gonna stop talking
about this anytime soon.

01:59.049 --> 02:01.861
Ms. Bell, I haven't seen you
on duty in a while.

02:01.885 --> 02:04.063
Well, I'm happy to be back.
Sharpen the skills.

02:04.087 --> 02:05.498
- Good breakfast?
- Ready to go.

02:05.522 --> 02:07.168
You need to have a good breakfast.

02:07.192 --> 02:09.101
- Mm-hmm.
- U.S. v. John Toe.

02:09.125 --> 02:10.836
- You mean Doe.
- Toe.

02:10.860 --> 02:12.204
Right. Doe. You said Toe.

02:12.228 --> 02:14.440
- Right, Toe.
- Doe.

02:14.464 --> 02:16.175
- Toe?
- That is correct, Your Honor.

02:16.199 --> 02:17.777
He was found with a toe?

02:17.801 --> 02:18.844
Yes, at the airport.

02:18.868 --> 02:21.247
Ms. Bell, are you okay?

02:21.271 --> 02:22.682
Yes, I'm fine.

02:22.706 --> 02:24.684
My... breakfast.

02:24.708 --> 02:25.885
I'm okay. Thank you.

02:25.909 --> 02:27.586
Your Honor, the defendant,
Douglas Bradshaw,

02:27.610 --> 02:30.356
was apprehended by TSA
with a toe in his cooler...

02:30.380 --> 02:31.357
Which is not illegal.

02:31.381 --> 02:34.026
Well, doesn't that depend on how
the toe got there, Ms. Bell?

02:34.050 --> 02:37.063
Mr. Bradshaw is
a human tissue broker with UNY.

02:37.087 --> 02:39.265
The transport of organs
and limbs is perfectly legal.

02:39.289 --> 02:42.001
We don't dispute that, but
Mr. Bradshaw was arrested

02:42.025 --> 02:44.437
because he became combative
with the TSA officers

02:44.461 --> 02:46.806
when they reasonably
questioned him about the toe...

02:46.830 --> 02:49.041
Because Mr. Bradshaw
was rushing to catch a flight

02:49.065 --> 02:51.644
to visit his sick mother and
was reasonably agitated

02:51.668 --> 02:53.179
at the suggestion
he had done anything wrong.

02:53.203 --> 02:54.380
He knocked over the cooler,

02:54.404 --> 02:56.816
and the toe rolled
through the screening area,

02:56.840 --> 02:59.418
approximately 25...

02:59.442 --> 03:00.453
feet.

03:00.477 --> 03:03.422
Why exactly would someone buy a toe?

03:03.446 --> 03:06.525
Well, uh, you could use the
bone for periodontal cement.

03:06.549 --> 03:08.094
There's surgical practice...

03:08.118 --> 03:10.196
toe augmentation, toe shortening...

03:10.220 --> 03:12.331
People get their toes shortened?

03:12.355 --> 03:14.233
Oh, yes. Toe jobs?

03:14.257 --> 03:17.069
Oh, yes, uh, definitely a growing market.

03:17.093 --> 03:19.305
If you think about it,
you have a hammer toe,

03:19.329 --> 03:20.706
but you wanna wear a strappy sandal...

03:20.730 --> 03:22.508
Okay, I think I get it.

03:22.532 --> 03:26.445
I will release Mr. Bradshaw
on a $10,000 bond.

03:26.469 --> 03:28.414
Hey, um, that toe...

03:28.438 --> 03:30.049
it's only worth, like, 500 bucks,

03:30.073 --> 03:31.484
but I got a bunch of ankles at home

03:31.508 --> 03:32.918
that should cover the rest.

03:32.942 --> 03:34.242
Cool?

03:37.247 --> 03:38.958
You were working a merchandise table

03:38.982 --> 03:40.581
at the music festival?

03:43.253 --> 03:44.630
Yes. I was.

03:44.654 --> 03:47.255
And that's where you met Ellie Mason.

03:48.425 --> 03:50.169
According to your statement,

03:50.193 --> 03:52.138
you went to the miniature golf course

03:52.162 --> 03:53.672
on the island together.

03:53.696 --> 03:55.641
- Yes?
- I work there.

03:55.665 --> 03:58.277
Did anybody see you there together?

03:58.301 --> 03:59.578
I don't know.

03:59.602 --> 04:00.880
You told the police

04:00.904 --> 04:03.449
you and Ellie went to Castle Williams

04:03.473 --> 04:05.551
after you left the golf course.

04:05.575 --> 04:08.687
Did you and Ellie walk to Castle
Williams after you left...

04:08.711 --> 04:10.956
Why do I have to keep saying it?

04:10.980 --> 04:14.326
The same things, over and over.

04:14.350 --> 04:16.695
Yes, we walked to Castle Williams.

04:16.719 --> 04:18.297
And as far as you're aware,

04:18.321 --> 04:21.801
nobody saw you together
at Castle Williams, right?

04:21.825 --> 04:23.791
No, that's not true.

04:25.061 --> 04:26.338
Someone saw us.

04:27.730 --> 04:29.475
The police have a witness.

04:31.468 --> 04:34.180
He says the police
told him there was a witness

04:34.204 --> 04:36.816
who saw him with Ellie at Castle Williams

04:36.840 --> 04:38.317
- right before she was killed.
- Jill.

04:38.341 --> 04:40.953
But that's not mentioned
anywhere in the complaint.

04:40.977 --> 04:42.688
I want to find out what happened
to this witness.

04:42.712 --> 04:43.856
Jill!

04:43.880 --> 04:45.394
I think we know what happened.

04:46.182 --> 04:49.528
The last time I saw her
was at the golf course.

04:49.552 --> 04:51.163
- I'm telling you...
- Steve.

04:51.187 --> 04:55.468
She said that she had to
find her friends, go home.

04:55.492 --> 04:58.370
She left and I stayed
and put some things away.

04:58.394 --> 05:00.539
You need to talk to us.

05:00.563 --> 05:02.074
- She left.
- Steve.

05:02.098 --> 05:03.242
I didn't see her again.

05:03.266 --> 05:05.110
Listen to me, we know what happened.

05:05.134 --> 05:06.412
We know, okay?

05:06.436 --> 05:07.913
We just need you to be honest with us.

05:07.937 --> 05:09.982
Did you leave the golf course with her?

05:10.006 --> 05:11.183
- I...
- We know.

05:11.207 --> 05:12.518
There's a witness.

05:12.542 --> 05:15.488
There's a witness, Steve, who saw
you with her at Castle Williams.

05:15.512 --> 05:17.423
You need to be honest with us now.

05:17.447 --> 05:19.425
What happened when you left Golf 'n Fun?

05:24.320 --> 05:25.753
We took...

05:27.690 --> 05:29.301
a walk?

05:29.325 --> 05:32.638
Okay. Good.

05:32.662 --> 05:34.039
Where'd you go?

05:34.063 --> 05:35.441
The only way we can help you

05:35.465 --> 05:36.876
is if you talk to us.

05:36.900 --> 05:38.344
Where'd you go?

05:38.368 --> 05:39.912
To Castle Williams.

05:39.936 --> 05:42.403
You and Ellie took a walk
to Castle Williams?

05:43.873 --> 05:45.217
Yes.

05:45.241 --> 05:49.288
This goes on for 14 hours
until you get to...

05:49.312 --> 05:51.056
...this.

05:51.080 --> 05:54.460
Ellie and I left the golf course.

05:54.484 --> 05:56.862
We walked to Castle Williams.

05:56.886 --> 05:59.164
She wanted to leave.

05:59.188 --> 06:02.434
I got angry. I hit her.

06:02.458 --> 06:05.804
I started... choking her.

06:05.828 --> 06:07.006
I choked her.

06:07.893 --> 06:09.769
I killed her.

06:11.100 --> 06:14.179
There was no witness. They made it up.

06:14.203 --> 06:16.949
This was a false confession.

06:20.610 --> 06:27.830
Synced & corrected by -robtor-
www.addic7ed.com

06:28.862 --> 06:31.641
Mason's body was found
early Sunday morning

06:31.666 --> 06:33.571
on Governor's Island by a member...

06:33.596 --> 06:34.839
Knox, Oliver. Come with me.

06:34.863 --> 06:36.041
Clear your schedules...

06:36.065 --> 06:38.014
postponements, continuances,
whatever you have to do.

06:38.038 --> 06:39.110
Whatever you need me to do.

06:39.134 --> 06:40.345
Us, 'cause I'm here, too.

06:40.369 --> 06:41.913
- This is important.
- Understood.

06:41.937 --> 06:43.014
- Work together on this.
- Of course.

06:43.038 --> 06:44.516
This is everything you need.

06:44.540 --> 06:46.451
This is... a map?

06:46.475 --> 06:47.485
You're off to a good start.

06:47.509 --> 06:48.587
We're on the Caldwell case, right,

06:48.611 --> 06:49.888
the murder on Governor's Island?

06:49.912 --> 06:51.356
What? God, no, that's capital murder.

06:51.380 --> 06:52.691
That's upstairs.

06:52.715 --> 06:55.160
You're speaking to a conference
of future lawyers...

06:55.184 --> 06:56.761
something that I agreed to with the bar

06:56.785 --> 06:58.830
a few months ago.

06:58.854 --> 07:01.566
I would go myself, but I don't want to.

07:01.590 --> 07:03.168
Do not embarrass this office or me,

07:03.192 --> 07:04.970
if you can help it,

07:04.994 --> 07:06.404
which you probably can't.

07:09.098 --> 07:10.642
And after the appeal was denied,

07:10.666 --> 07:12.844
the case was remanded
back to the district court

07:12.868 --> 07:13.945
for further proceedings,

07:13.969 --> 07:16.214
which was a bench trial.

07:16.238 --> 07:17.704
Which I won.

07:20.676 --> 07:21.987
Won what?

07:22.597 --> 07:24.723
- Trial.
- What's trial?

07:25.387 --> 07:26.725
Do you remember how I was...

07:26.749 --> 07:28.526
My sister has a bird!

07:28.550 --> 07:30.428
Any other questions?

07:30.452 --> 07:32.797
Why don't you go after the banks?

07:32.821 --> 07:35.200
My dad says you don't go after the banks.

07:35.224 --> 07:36.835
- We do.
- No, you don't.

07:36.859 --> 07:38.203
- We do.
- No, you don't.

07:38.227 --> 07:39.804
- We do.
- No, you don't.

07:39.828 --> 07:41.106
Why don't you like birds?!

07:41.130 --> 07:42.574
Who wants to see a magic trick?

07:42.598 --> 07:44.142
Me!

07:45.339 --> 07:47.669
Thank you, guys. That was great.

07:47.693 --> 07:48.813
Tough crowd.

07:48.837 --> 07:50.382
Well, it's a good thing

07:50.406 --> 07:51.983
you can make a quarter disappear.

07:52.007 --> 07:54.319
- I need to learn that trick.
- I can teach you.

07:54.343 --> 07:55.920
We should really be
getting back, but thank you.

07:55.944 --> 07:57.422
We appreciate the opportunity to come in

07:57.446 --> 07:58.657
and talk about the work that we do...

07:58.681 --> 08:00.325
Which is nothing compared
to the work you do.

08:00.349 --> 08:01.793
That's so nice of you to say.

08:01.817 --> 08:02.927
And so totally true.

08:04.186 --> 08:06.398
Uh, hey, if you ever need help
with anything...

08:06.422 --> 08:09.734
legal or whatever...
we'd be happy to help.

08:09.758 --> 08:13.238
If you wanna take our information
or my information...

08:13.262 --> 08:15.674
Yeah. Okay. Great.

08:15.698 --> 08:17.542
Assuming I get in some legal trouble.

08:17.566 --> 08:18.610
Let's hope not.

08:18.634 --> 08:19.811
Or let's. Who's to say?

08:24.373 --> 08:26.117
Serena Nazari.

08:27.342 --> 08:29.721
I better go before one of them
makes a break for it.

08:36.818 --> 08:38.063
What?

08:38.087 --> 08:39.953
I can show you the quarter trick, too.

08:43.125 --> 08:44.803
Welcome to the War Room.

08:44.827 --> 08:46.204
We have a War Room?

08:46.228 --> 08:48.740
- I thought this was storage.
- That, too.

08:48.764 --> 08:49.941
But there's a working table

08:49.965 --> 08:52.277
under here somewhere and some chairs.

08:52.301 --> 08:53.378
And the Ark of the Covenant.

08:53.402 --> 08:54.813
Why do we need a War Room?

08:54.837 --> 08:56.915
The single most difficult
piece of evidence

08:56.939 --> 08:59.818
to overcome in any criminal proceeding

08:59.842 --> 09:00.852
is a confession.

09:00.876 --> 09:02.787
It is why we have the Fifth Amendment.

09:02.811 --> 09:04.522
It is why we have Miranda rights.

09:04.546 --> 09:06.725
It is the vast, immovable object

09:06.749 --> 09:07.926
in the middle of our case,

09:07.950 --> 09:09.427
and there's no easy way over it

09:09.451 --> 09:11.763
or around it or underneath it.

09:11.787 --> 09:14.199
Our only real chance
is removing it altogether.

09:14.223 --> 09:15.533
A Motion to Suppress.

09:15.557 --> 09:16.634
Exactly.

09:16.658 --> 09:18.503
If we can get the confession thrown out,

09:18.527 --> 09:20.205
we can get Steve's case thrown out.

09:20.229 --> 09:21.673
The case is the confession.

09:21.697 --> 09:22.974
So we attack the confession.

09:22.998 --> 09:24.409
Steve was read his Miranda rights.

09:24.433 --> 09:26.010
He waived his right to an attorney.

09:26.034 --> 09:28.379
But that doesn't mean
the confession was voluntary.

09:28.403 --> 09:30.582
Our job now is to show that it wasn't.

09:30.606 --> 09:32.250
We treat the interrogation itself

09:32.274 --> 09:34.552
- like a crime.
- Yes.

09:34.576 --> 09:36.910
Which means we start with the victim.

09:42.985 --> 09:44.863
I... I was so tired.

09:44.887 --> 09:47.432
- I know.
- I felt like I was losing my mind.

09:47.456 --> 09:49.033
You were. That was the point.

09:49.057 --> 09:50.802
Why? Why did they do this?

09:50.826 --> 09:52.504
Because somewhere in the beginning,

09:52.528 --> 09:54.973
they attached themselves
to the idea you were it.

09:54.997 --> 09:56.141
From that point forward,

09:56.165 --> 09:58.576
either they were gonna break or you were.

09:58.600 --> 10:00.500
I broke.

10:02.504 --> 10:04.616
Yeah, they got in my head, and I broke.

10:04.640 --> 10:06.351
A lot of people do, Steve,

10:06.375 --> 10:08.052
more than you can possibly imagine.

10:08.076 --> 10:09.354
I don't want you to feel...

10:09.378 --> 10:13.547
I confessed to a crime I did not commit.

10:15.918 --> 10:17.726
I didn't kill that girl.

10:18.754 --> 10:20.365
I did not kill that girl.

10:20.389 --> 10:21.966
Steve...

10:21.990 --> 10:24.903
I know how difficult this is,

10:24.927 --> 10:28.706
but I need you to tell me everything
you can about the interrogation.

10:28.730 --> 10:30.230
Everything.

10:31.867 --> 10:33.600
Okay, um...

10:34.703 --> 10:36.953
The room was small.

10:37.539 --> 10:39.284
I felt like I-I couldn't move,

10:39.308 --> 10:41.319
and there were all
these people in there...

10:41.343 --> 10:43.454
the... the two detectives the whole time,

10:43.478 --> 10:45.256
but other cops coming in and out.

10:45.280 --> 10:46.825
It was hot.

10:46.849 --> 10:49.627
I was hungry, thirsty.

10:49.651 --> 10:50.929
I was hungover.

10:50.953 --> 10:52.931
E-Every time I asked for water,

10:52.955 --> 10:55.597
they gave me a little cup.

10:56.758 --> 10:58.536
Um... I mean, h-how many times

10:58.560 --> 11:00.594
are you gonna ask a cop for water?

11:02.130 --> 11:04.843
They... They told me
that they had evidence,

11:04.867 --> 11:06.144
not just witnesses.

11:06.168 --> 11:07.312
They had my prints.

11:07.336 --> 11:09.614
They brought in a forensics expert.

11:09.638 --> 11:12.083
He said all the marks on Ellie's neck

11:12.107 --> 11:13.585
fit my hands...

11:13.609 --> 11:15.086
a perfect match.

11:15.110 --> 11:16.821
He showed me the lab report.

11:16.845 --> 11:18.389
That "expert" was just a file clerk

11:18.413 --> 11:19.524
in the police station.

11:19.548 --> 11:20.992
The lab report was fake, too.

11:21.016 --> 11:22.360
And they... they... they kept saying

11:22.384 --> 11:25.530
that they were going to help me,

11:25.554 --> 11:29.300
and they... they said that I
was in, uh, real trouble,

11:29.324 --> 11:32.704
but if I was honest, they could help.

11:32.728 --> 11:35.073
And I-I didn't know who to talk to.

11:35.097 --> 11:37.889
I haven't seen my folks for years.

11:38.901 --> 11:40.011
I was scared.

11:41.760 --> 11:43.581
He was kicked out of his house
when he was 14,

11:43.605 --> 11:46.951
abusive stepfather,
never finished high school.

11:46.975 --> 11:49.087
He lives with his grandmother,
who is sick,

11:49.111 --> 11:51.757
but seems to be the only one
who's ever cared about this kid.

11:52.881 --> 11:54.492
What ha... What happens now?

11:54.516 --> 11:57.495
We pull all this together,
we write a motion,

11:57.519 --> 12:00.598
we file it, we argue it,

12:00.622 --> 12:02.033
and then we wait.

12:08.864 --> 12:10.463
Ugh.

